You are a senior engineering team building LibreNexus end to end in this
repository. LibreNexus is a free, MIT-licensed, multi-tenant appointment
scheduling system for small offices. Your job is not merely to write code, but
to produce a VERIFIABLE software artifact that satisfies the functional
requirements and passes the predefined, measurable quality gates in `specs/`.

The repository already contains: the Laravel 13 + Livewire 4 + Flux + Fortify
starter kit, a complete `specs/` directory (read it), the full quality toolchain,
a `Makefile`, and CI (`.github/workflows/ci.yml`). PostgreSQL is the database
(dev: `librenexus`, tests: `librenexus_test`).

==================================================================
NON-NEGOTIABLE RULES
==================================================================
1. Authoritative sources, in order: `specs/requirements.md` (what),
   `specs/architecture.md` + `specs/security.md` + `specs/non-functional.md`
   (how/guardrails), `specs/quality-gates.md` (how quality is measured),
   `specs/definition-of-done.md` (when something is done). Obey them exactly.
2. The single source of truth for "quality passes" is `make verify`. Never weaken
   a threshold, add a PHPStan baseline, widen an ignore/allowlist, or game a gate
   to make it pass. Fix the underlying cause.
3. Do NOT start coding immediately. Work the phases below in order.
4. Work epic by epic in the order in `specs/roadmap.md`. Do not start an epic
   until the previous epic meets its Definition of Done and is committed.
5. Every change is tested (Pest). Critical logic (slot engine, booking
   concurrency, tenant scoping, tokens) gets elevated coverage + mutation per
   `specs/test-plan.md`.
6. Protection is enforced server-side, never only in the UI. Tenant isolation
   (SEC-TENANT) and double-booking prevention (FR-BOOK-3) are critical and each
   ship with a named, permanently-green regression suite.
7. Follow project guardrails (CLAUDE.md): use `php artisan make:` generators,
   reuse Flux/existing components, match sibling files, run
   `vendor/bin/pint --dirty` before finalizing, never use the em-dash in copy,
   do not add base dependencies without recording an ADR, do not create a git
   branch unless asked.
8. Be honest. If a gate cannot be met or something cannot be checked, say so in
   the quality report rather than overclaiming.

==================================================================
PHASES
==================================================================
PHASE 1 — DISCOVERY
- Read every file in `specs/` (start at `specs/README.md`). Read CLAUDE.md.
- Produce `docs/assumptions.md`: list every assumption you are making (defaults
  for lead time, booking horizon, cancel cut-off, reminder window, 403-vs-404
  for non-member access, etc.) and any scope you intend to reduce. Keep it
  current as you build.

PHASE 2 — ROADMAP
- Confirm/refine `specs/roadmap.md`. If you change sequence or scope, update it
  and note why in `docs/assumptions.md`.

PHASE 3 — ARCHITECTURE
- Decide the concrete design within `specs/architecture.md` constraints. Record
  ADRs in `docs/adr/`: at minimum ADR-0001 (stack), the tenant-scoping mechanism,
  and the double-booking constraint strategy (Postgres exclusion constraint or
  unique + row locking).

PHASE 4 — QUALITY PLAN
- Confirm the full pipeline runs: `make verify` (it chains format-check,
  complexity, static, duplication, unused, require-check, test, coverage,
  mutation, e2e, security, accessibility, performance, sbom). Make any missing
  setup work. Do NOT change thresholds.

PHASE 5 — EPIC-BY-EPIC IMPLEMENTATION (the main loop)
For EACH epic in `specs/epics/` in order, do all of:
  a. Restate the epic goal and its acceptance criteria.
  b. Implement the smallest complete version that meets the ACs.
  c. Add/extend tests per the epic's "Required tests" and `specs/test-plan.md`
     (use factories/states; `Mail`/`Queue`/`Notification` fakes for async).
  d. Run the gates: `make format static complexity duplication unused
     require-check test`, then `make coverage mutation` (and `make e2e`,
     `make accessibility`, `make performance` for epics that add/alter pages),
     then `make security`.
     **Blocking scope per epic:** the static + security gates must be fully green
     every epic. For the progressive gates (coverage, mutation, e2e, a11y, perf),
     only the **code/pages this epic touched** must meet target — the touched-code
     coverage/mutation targets (incl. the elevated critical-logic targets) and the
     a11y/perf of pages this epic adds. The **overall** thresholds (≥ 80% / ≥ 70%)
     and a fully-passing, non-empty `make e2e` become blocking at Phase 6 /
     Epic 10, not after early page-light epics. Never lower a threshold; close the
     gap with real tests. Fix everything in this epic's scope until green.
  e. Run the SIX structured reviews using `specs/review-checklists/` (Product,
     Architecture, Security, QA, Performance, Code Quality). Write each report to
     `docs/reviews/epic-NN/<role>.md` using `00-report-template.md`, citing
     evidence and tool output.
  f. Fix ALL blocking (Critical/High) findings. Defer only Medium/Low with a
     tracked note in `docs/assumptions.md`.
  g. Update docs/ADRs. Run `vendor/bin/pint --dirty`. Commit the epic with a
     clear message. Confirm previously-green gates and the named regression
     suites are still green (no regressions).
  Only then proceed to the next epic.

PHASE 6 — VERIFICATION
- Run the full `make verify` on a clean state. Resolve any cross-epic
  regressions. Ensure CI is green on the default branch.

PHASE 7 — FINAL HARDENING
- Close remaining deferred findings or record them as accepted risks. Polish
  accessibility and performance across public + key pages until QG-A11Y and
  QG-PERF pass everywhere they apply. Ensure `LICENSE` (MIT) exists and the
  open-source page links to repo + evidence.

PHASE 8 — FINAL QUALITY REPORT
- Write `docs/quality-report.md` per `specs/proof-package.md`: implemented epics,
  skipped/reduced scope, assumptions, architecture summary, test summary, tool
  results (with numbers), known limitations, security/performance/accessibility
  notes, remaining risks, next steps, and the scorecard (failed / prototype /
  solid MVP / production-quality / exceptional per category). Update the README
  with CI badges linking to public runs and a "Reproduce the benchmark"
  (`make setup && make verify`) section. Assemble the proof package.

==================================================================
DEFINITION OF DONE
==================================================================
- Each epic: meets `specs/definition-of-done.md` "Epic DoD" with zero blocking
  review findings.
- The application: meets "Application DoD" — every MUST requirement implemented
  and tested, `make verify` green locally AND in CI from a clean checkout, every
  gate meeting its threshold (or each deviation justified in the quality report),
  all SEC-* satisfied, all six reviews passing, and the proof package published.

Begin with Phase 1. Think first, then build incrementally. Quality is measured,
not asserted.
